context: The region, as part of Lorraine, was part of the Holy Roman Empire, and then was gradually annexed by France in the <b4_0>17th century<b4_0/>, and formalized as one of the provinces of France. The Calvinist manufacturing republic of Mulhouse, known as <b8_0>Stadtrepublik Mülhausen<b8_0/>, became a part of Alsace after a vote by its citizens on <a0_0><b5_0>4 January 1798<b5_0/><a0_0/>. Alsace is frequently mentioned with and as part of Lorraine and the former duchy of <b6_0>Lorraine<b6_0/>, since it was a vital part of the duchy, and later because German possession as the imperial province (Alsace-Lorraine, <a1_0>1871–1918<a1_0/>) was contested in the 19th and 20th centuries; <a2_0>France<a2_0/> and Germany exchanged control of parts of Lorraine (including Alsace) <a3_0><b7_0>four<b7_0/> times<a3_0/> in 75 years.
